{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"23ad3d55-c33c-4dcd-a615-4d4e79803669","content":"Yes, these are known **MSTest v4 behavioral changes** (compile-clean but break at runtime):\n\n## 1. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it no longer has a meaningful `TestName` (it's `null`). Previously it carried the name of the first test. This is by design since class init isn't tied to any single test.\n\n**Fix:** Don't access `TestContext.TestName` in `ClassInitialize`. If you need it for logging, use the class name or a constant:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassSetup(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is null in v4 class-level context\n    var name = context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName;\n    System.Console.WriteLine($\"Setting up for: {name}\");\n}\n```\n\n## 2. Discovery errors\n\nIn MSTest v4, **test discovery is stricter**. Common causes:\n\n- The `TestContext` property must have `{ get; set; }` (yours is fine).\n- `[ClassInitialize]` methods that **throw** during discovery will cause all tests in that class to fail as \"not discovered.\" Your `TestName` access likely returns `null` and if any downstream code does `.Length` or similar, it throws — killing discovery for the class.\n\n**Fix:** Once you fix the `ClassInitialize` crash above, discovery should recover.\n\nWould you like me to apply the fix to your file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"615897c7-5dae-4a6e-bfbf-b53a56d4c536","outputTokens":373,"requestId":"E3C2:1EA0D0:D64828:F3644E:6A0542F1"},"id":"92fec8b2-48f5-4e69-b298-87b092bca868","timestamp":"2026-05-14T03:35:23.929Z","parentId":"6f543d3e-0ee0-4853-aa80-3061038b2221"}
